The paper deals with the application of deep learning to the problem of liquid perception and reasoning, which is a key component for enabling robots to handle liquids using robust, closed-loop controllers. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper applies fully-convolutional deep neural networks to the tasks of detecting and tracking liquids, which suggests that it may also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also deals with the application of AI and deep learning, which suggests that it may belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper evaluates three models, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of enabling robots to handle liquids using closed-loop controllers, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
